Addition:

Food Group 5: Digestive and Metabolic boosting food

For digestion, I usually kick start my morning with 1/2 lemon water that I dilute with warm water and a spoonful of chia seeds. I usually let it rest for about 30 minutes before I go on with my breakfast.

To help with the bloating and flatulence from fibrous food, I usually just drink loads of water, do some massages, exercise, and take a hot shower. Idk but for me, doing crunches really helps with flatulence

Now, I’m not gonna sugarcoat anything. If you are not used to consuming that much fibre, you’ll get a little bloated since your system is working so hard to break down all those fibres but everything will get better when you secrete everything out the next morning
For leafy greens, I consume about 100grams/day. As for fruits, I don’t really measure them but I often eat either 2 tangerines + 5 cherry tomatoes or a full fruit platter of pineapple and dragonfruit
I also eat fruits as snacks. Mostly tomatoes, tangerines, dragonfruit, and pineapple. Personally, pineapple holds a special place but I will elaborate it on the section (digestive-boosting food)

My favourite source of fibre is leafy greens! Kale, broccoli, spinach, you name it! Sometimes I eat them raw, turn them into pesto, or simply sauté and steam them. Very versatile and blends easily with anything you season them with (though I also eat other veggies)

Food group 4: Fibres

Fibre is important as it helps your digestive system and helps with constipation. Not only that, but it also keeps you full longer as your body takes a longer time to break down fibrous food.

♡Tip: Tweaking oils

Want to use oil for seasonings such as infused oil, olive oil, and sesame oil but are afraid of the cals? Just add your oil last/after you finished cooking so the smell won’t cook away. Hence, you will need a smaller amount to season your food.

Now, as aforementioned, I rarely consume red meat. Why? Because red meat is high in saturated fat, similarly to full-fat dairy products (I don’t consume dairy AT ALL as I am lactose intolerant so I won’t get too deep into it) https://t.co/FFdCzmO8Nw
Polyunsaturated fats are divided into omega-3 and omega-6. My favourite sources for omega-3 are salmon (sashimi), chia seeds and flax seeds whilst omega-6 are corn, sunflower oil, walnuts, and eggs.
Monounsaturated fats can be found in various different items, but my favourites are extra virgin olive oil, sesame oil, and avocados
However, just like carbs, there are ‘good’ fat and ‘bad’ fat. Healthy fats are divided into Polyunsaturated fats and Monounsaturated fats. Both maintain your cholesterol level
Now now, I know this is the most feared category. But flash news: consuming fat aids weight loss since it provides satiety. Meaning that it prevents binges https://t.co/6ZiDwvumZZ
I don’t have a scale for exact measurements but I either eat 1 chicken breast a day (average size), 2 fish (small-sized fish, or roughly 150grams of fillets), or 2 blocks of tofu/tempeh a day.

For protein, I mostly grill, boil, or steam them. Never fried. As for tofu and tempeh, I incorporate them into my own tweaked and healthier version of stir-fries like this one
https://t.co/yRyYEFvtrl
I usually do 1-2 plant-based days a week, and also rarely eat red meat. Probably once a month AT MOST. There’s a reason for this and it will later be explained in the next food group category.

Other than from beans and peas that I incorporate into my carbs, I mostly eat lean protein, such as fish, seafood, chicken breast and vegan protein options such as tofu and tempeh. (Sometimes eggs too) https://t.co/M2uSuLBtHw

Food group 2: Protein

This is probably the most important food group if you’re trying to build muscle/toned up through strength training https://t.co/48lIrssB15

Though I choose the healthiest option of carbs possible, moderation is still the key. I eat 50-70grams (raw) of carbs a day. Complex carbs fill me up faster anyways. (50-70grams is the literal weight, not the nutritional values)

Complex carbs of my choice are including lentils, quinoa, tricolour rice and legumes mixture, and rolled oats. Some of these options like lentils, quinoa, and oat, provide iron if you’re anaemic as well! Treating my anaemia increase my strength during workouts. https://t.co/eiiYbXfS0N
The easiest way (for me) to recognise refined carbs is “if it’s white, it serves me no good” such as white rice, white bread, white sugar, etc.

To put it simply, eating refined carbs only provides you satiation for a short amount of time. You’ll get tired easier, you’ll get hungry sooner, and they also contain little to no fibre. Hindering you from getting that healthy digestive system. Yikes.

However, there are such things as Refined carbs vs. Complex carbs. Choose complex carbs every time. Why? you ask. Because your body works longer breaking those complex carbs into simple sugar, keeps you feeling satisfied for a longer period. https://t.co/Q09Xjj3Iqb

Food group 1: Carbs

Carbs are not your enemies, esp if you workout a lot. Your body turns carbs into simple sugar, therefore releasing insulin that will help those sugars transfer to your blood cells.

But why choose those foods when u can starve and get skinny you say?

To answer that q, I’m going to divide this diet explanation into 5 parts. Carbs, protein, fat, fibres, and metabolic and digestive-boosting foods.
Now, I’m not gonna lie, healthy whole foods cost me a little more compared to regular foods. For example, where I live, white rice is way cheaper than tricolour rice (black, red, and brown rice)

To eliminate my fear, I also incorporate some simple scientific research. I usually looked up medical journals or experiment-based statistic results that are conducted and approved by medical professionals.

Since I’m trying to be kinder to my body, I stopped counting calories. This is probably the hardest part of it all, shifting my mindset. However, I overcame my fear by watching vs model vlogs or healthy-eating wieiad videos.
